          <td bgcolor="" valign="top" width="1"><img src="/magination/gfx/trans_header1.gif" width="22" height="2" vspace="0" hspace="0" border="0"></td>
          <td bgcolor="" valign="top"><!-- #BeginEditable "Body" --> 
            <table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0">
  <tr>
    <td>
      <table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="2" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
        <tr>
          <td>
            <table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="2">
              <tr> 
                <td class="chpurple"><font class="h1font"><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 border=0 width=100%><TR><td><font class="h1font">Articles</td><form method='post' action=''><td align='right' valign='bottom'><select name='select' onChange='go(this)'><option selected>More DeckTech Articles</option><option value='#'> </option><option value='/swccg/articles/index.php3'>Star Wars: CCG</option><option value='/lotr/articles/articles.php'>Lord of the Rings</option><option value='/magination/articles/articles.php'>Magi-Nation Duel</option></select></td></form></tr></table></font></td></tr></table></td></tr><tr><td><table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="3"><tr><td><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> A Breakdown of Perpetual Motion<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/magination/gfx/star3.gif" width="21" height="22" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/magination/gfx/star3.gif" width="21" height="22" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/magination/gfx/star3.gif" width="21" height="22" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/magination/gfx/star3.gif" width="21" height="22" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(4.25)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/magination/main/mpage.php?member=9064'>Danny "Woven" Young</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/magination/main/mpage.php?member=9064&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> February 13, 2002</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont">  Before I begin, I want to say that I DO know the risks involved with this type of deck, so you do not need to tell me the dangers of building off an opponent. Now...<br>
 First off, what is Perpetual Motion? The effect itself just means that anything happening at the start of your turn happens at the start of an opponent&#39;s turn. Perpetual Motion when used to describe a deck or combo means that you have your effects set to take place at your opponents turn and cause a burst of free energy. And while it can be hard to pull off, when you do, it is very fun and rewarding.<br>
 Jagt and Gargagnor have this effect built in. It allows Crag Quor, Yebed, Xamf, and Gratch to trigger at the start of your opponent&#39;s turn... but why?? The answer is easy when you think that you control the energy for the next turn. Triggering effects without Perpetual Motion means that you have to trust your opponent to leave the energy exactly how you want it... but if they know what you&#39;re doing (which they will) they will prevent it. And all it takes is one wrong energy to stop you cold. That said, you control all energy at the beginning of the next turn. This is true for all players. <br>
 The problem with this type of strategy is that the wording on your cards are very odd.... if your smallest creature is larger than the largest opposing creature?? How often does that happen? That is where the next key component of Motion comes in. Chogus. <br>
 We all looked at this card with a bewildered look on our faces at first, but this is why it is needed to make Motion work. The odd wording in the last paragraph, with Chogus in play, becomes this- if your smallest creature is larger than the SMALLEST opposing creature. Now we&#39;re getting somewhere. <br>
 Here&#39;s a basic layout of the field: You have in play a Gragagnor, a Chogus, a Xamratch, a Crag Quor, and a Yebed. Your opponent has an Iximin, a Megathan, and a few creatures inbetween; all creatures are at starting energy when your opponent&#39;s turn rolls around. Your smallest is 4 and their smallest is three. This triggers Xamf and Gratch. Your magi gains a free four energize and all your creatures (except Gratch) gain one. At the same time, Crag Quor(your largest) is smaller than their largest (Megathan), so Yebed triggers so the opponent&#39;s side loses an energy apiece, and Crag Quor shoots up 4 energy. Don&#39;t forget that all this happens at the same time, so you don&#39;t have to worry abnout Gratch throwing things off. The results are even better when you have multiples of each creature in play. Imagine you have all 3 Gratch and all 3 Xamf. Well, well, aren&#39;t we happy now?<br>
 If a kink gets into the system, such as, your smallest creature bacomes one energy, just kamikazee him. Or better yet, play Kybar&#39;s Echo first to get him back in at full power. After a few turns, everything will be upside down. When that happens, kill off your Chogus. This restores your cards to normal wording so they can trigger again the next turn. In one experience of mine, I cast Echo and then kazied two creatures and then attacked one of my own creatures to defeat him. Then I resummoned those creatures to start the combo again. This brings up another benefit of Perpetual Motion; you can get it to work your very first turn, or the first turn your new magi comes in because you don&#39;t have to attack anything. You can play creatures and reap the benefits as soon as you finish drawing cards.<br>
 Perpetual Motion is not as hard as some people make it out to be. I tried it and now have a fun AND powerful deck. After a few turns, you can have dozens of free energy. And what can your opponent do about it? Ormagon? Cataclysm? They will kill off every creature, but you&#39;ll be fine. You just got 12 energy from your Xamf team and they just lost 10 to clear the board. <br>
 The final thing you need for this type of deck is the right magi. Most players use Targ&#39;n and Jagt beacuse they start with half of what you need. The last magi is up to choice; I chose Hok because he starts with a Gargagnor, but you can pretty much throw in whatever you want. This is a dangerous deck to play, but with the right tweaking, your deck will be able to muscle its way out if Motion isn&#39;t working. Give it a try and you may be surprised... I was! <br></font><BR><font class="bfont"> <A HREF='/magination/articles/articles.php?id=3304&view=1'>Read the Reviews</a><font class="bfont"> | <A HREF='/magination/articles/articles.php'>Back to List</A></font><p><font class="bfont"> <b>You must be a member to contribute to Decktech.</b>  <p>Please <a href='/magination/main/join.php'> become a registered member</a></font></td></tr></table></td>
        </tr>
      </table>
